04:20.334 --> 04:28.303
I really, really like 1940s music and would go to the mat for Ella Fitzgerald or Dean Morton.

04:28.403 --> 04:30.045
So I kind of have eclectic taste.

04:31.507 --> 04:32.448
But I'm here this morning.

04:32.468 --> 04:34.450
I'm going to make a bold theological claim.

04:35.202 --> 04:38.546
because I think I can have the authority to do that because of how much I live music.

04:38.927 --> 04:45.615
And that is one of the best songs of all time is sung by the incomparable Donnie Osmond.

04:46.896 --> 04:47.857
Okay?

04:47.878 --> 04:50.120
And I'm wondering if anyone can guess the song that I made.

04:50.861 --> 04:53.004
Some of you in your hearts know exactly where I'm going.

04:54.165 --> 04:54.686
That's right.

04:55.126 --> 04:58.150
It's I'll make a man out of view from the Disney classic Mulan.

04:58.711 --> 05:00.253
And you guys know what I'm talking about.

05:00.293 --> 05:01.194
Don't act like you don't.

05:01.314 --> 05:02.616
I know you've seen Mulan.

05:02.716 --> 05:04.658
I know you know the song I'm talking about.

05:04.738 --> 05:07.864
It is the best song for any situation.

05:08.325 --> 05:16.941
If you need to hype yourself up, you put on, I'll make a man out of you, Sam is shaking his head, because he can't believe that this is where we're at, but stay with me, okay?

05:16.961 --> 05:20.207
It is, it is a, for those who, has anyone not seen move on?

05:21.449 --> 05:22.110
Oh, Andy, why?

05:22.150 --> 05:23.894
Okay, a quick rundown.

05:24.855 --> 05:26.258
They're training for war.

05:26.370 --> 05:29.113
They're fighting, they're getting ready to go to war.

05:29.373 --> 05:31.695
It's the Chinese people that've been invaded by the Huns.

05:32.356 --> 05:35.078
And they need Donnie Osman to come in and whip them into shape.

05:35.519 --> 05:42.525
And so Donnie Osman comes in and he starts singing about let's get down to business, to defeat the Huns.

05:42.585 --> 05:43.406
Yes, thank you.

05:43.987 --> 05:45.708
So they're trying to whip them into shape.

05:45.828 --> 05:50.032
And when that song comes on, it's just this powerful hype song for me.

05:50.052 --> 05:51.273
It does something to me.

05:52.154 --> 05:56.178
It's like there's this drum montage and there's this buildup.

05:56.482 --> 06:00.308
And it's really intense and it's talking about how we're going to make a man out of you, right?

06:00.348 --> 06:01.470
It's a training anthem.

06:02.531 --> 06:03.853
This is how you grow stronger.

06:04.134 --> 06:05.235
This is how you get tougher.

06:05.295 --> 06:09.442
They're training for something, like they're training for intense battle.

06:09.642 --> 06:12.887
They're getting ready to do something new.

06:14.129 --> 06:22.642
And if we're honest, I think that song captures something about what we believe instinctively about growth.

06:23.906 --> 06:33.615
that becoming better requires a little bit of pressure, that transformation requires training, that strength is built through resistance.

06:34.977 --> 06:46.868
And in Hebrews 12, the writer uses almost the same kind of language, but it's not about soldiers, it's not about battle, it's about being sons and daughters of God.

06:48.950 --> 06:52.594
So you heard me say the word discipline a lot.

06:52.898 --> 06:55.861
I want to acknowledge that that word can make some of us feel some type of way, maybe.

06:57.123 --> 06:59.826
Discipline is not a fun church word.

07:00.386 --> 07:02.509
It's not something that gives us the warm fuzzies.

07:03.850 --> 07:10.738
When we hear discipline, we often think punishment, or maybe we think anger, right?

07:10.758 --> 07:18.386
We think about someone getting in trouble, but that's not actually how the author of Hebrews is using the word.

07:19.586 --> 07:27.015
See, the writer is reminding us, reminding believers, reminding Christians that God disciplines those he loves.

07:27.576 --> 07:29.538
And he does that because they're his children.

07:30.820 --> 07:30.920
Okay?

07:32.282 --> 07:34.405
This is corrective, it's not punitive.

07:35.686 --> 07:35.987
All right?

07:36.267 --> 07:37.468
It's a way of training us.

07:38.209 --> 07:42.775
And I particularly like verse 11, where he says, no discipline seems pleasant at the time.

07:44.097 --> 07:45.138
It's painful.

07:45.986 --> 07:52.214
Later on, however, it produces a harvest of righteousness and peace for those who have been trained by it.

07:53.436 --> 07:54.357
So you're tracking with me.

07:54.578 --> 07:56.180
This is not about punishment.

07:56.200 --> 07:58.443
This is not about shaming you.

07:58.463 --> 08:01.166
This is not about us being reprimanded.

08:01.247 --> 08:02.688
This is about training.

08:02.749 --> 08:06.233
We are people in progress.

08:07.014 --> 08:07.916
But I don't know about you.

08:07.936 --> 08:09.778
When I experience correction,

08:10.274 --> 08:19.805
When I experience someone telling me that I should have done something differently or better, when someone points out that I have messed up, my first response is not, ah, yes, beautiful growth.

08:20.606 --> 08:22.068
How fun, how exciting.

08:23.169 --> 08:24.131
No, it hurts.

08:24.691 --> 08:25.612
Like, it hurts.

08:25.693 --> 08:26.894
Discipline is uncomfortable.

08:27.234 --> 08:30.458
And my first instinct is, what did I do wrong?

08:32.180 --> 08:33.742
Is God disappointed in me?

08:33.762 --> 08:36.946
Is this punishment?

08:38.690 --> 08:49.723
And I love this passage in Hebrews because it's almost like the writer is anticipating those kinds of questions from us because he reminds us again and again, God disciplines those he loves.

08:50.604 --> 08:54.709
And if you endure discipline, then that means God is treating you as his child.

08:55.950 --> 08:59.274
So in other words, discipline is not rejection.

08:59.314 --> 09:02.418
Rejection pushes you away.

09:02.882 --> 09:11.231
Rejection says you don't belong here anymore, but discipline in this passage is described as the action of a father towards his child.

09:11.532 --> 09:13.113
This is not God closing the door.

09:13.153 --> 09:18.799
This is not God saying he doesn't want anything to do with us until we can get right.

09:20.461 --> 09:23.024
This is God refusing to leave us unchanged.

09:25.307 --> 09:28.370
God disciplines us because he's not done with us yet.

09:29.122 --> 09:31.305
And this is very, very different than punishment.

09:31.325 --> 09:33.147
All right, so we've laid that foundation, all right?

09:33.187 --> 09:41.598
We know that when we're talking about discipline, what we're talking about is God shaping us so that we can share in holiness.

09:43.881 --> 09:47.726
God is disciplining us so that we can share in holiness.

09:49.909 --> 09:56.978
So we're gonna come back to Hebrews in a moment, but I want us to look now at our Matthew's passage in the Lord's Prayer.

09:57.730 --> 10:00.955
Because all Lent and season, we're going to be dissecting the Lord's Prayer.

10:00.975 --> 10:05.643
We're going to be trying to figure out what it was that Jesus is teaching us by reciting this prayer to us.

10:06.725 --> 10:11.473
In Matthew 6, in the middle of the Sermon on the Mount, Jesus teaches his disciples how to pray.

10:11.513 --> 10:17.042
And he doesn't use very churchy religious language, and this is not like

10:17.186 --> 10:18.588
a whole lot of repetition going on.

10:18.608 --> 10:21.251
Like he's giving them a formula of like how they need to be praying.

10:21.271 --> 10:28.961
And it's got a rhythm to it and it reveals in that rhythm in the words that Jesus says, it reveals what God's priorities are.

10:29.762 --> 10:30.083
All right.

10:31.004 --> 10:39.575
And the very first thing that Jesus teaches his disciples to say in prayer, our father who art in heaven, hallowed be thy name.

10:41.237 --> 10:42.178
Hallowed be thy name.

10:43.820 --> 10:45.202
Before we get to daily bread,

10:46.434 --> 10:54.326
before we get to forgiveness, before we get to deliverance, we first have to look at holiness.

10:56.669 --> 10:57.491
Holiness, okay?

10:58.572 --> 11:08.507
So it turns out that holiness and discipline are connected, but before we dive into the how and the wise, I'm gonna pray for us one more time, and we're really, really gonna dig in, okay?

11:12.213 --> 11:12.914
Holy God.

11:13.058 --> 11:22.790
We ask that you would meet us in this moment now that we've kind of laid groundwork, Father, for where we're going, now that we are prepared to discuss what it means to love and be loved by a holy God.

11:22.810 --> 11:25.033
Father, would you open our hearts to hear from you?

11:25.834 --> 11:28.798
Jesus, we know that you're in this space and we're ready for you to talk to us.

11:30.020 --> 11:30.580
We love you too.

11:31.341 --> 11:31.622
Amen.

11:33.284 --> 11:33.985
Okay.

11:34.005 --> 11:36.948
So, Halloween is not a word that comes up often.

11:38.250 --> 11:41.394
In fact, I've only ever heard it in this context.

11:41.602 --> 11:46.106
I used to think that it was connected to Halloween as a child, and so the Lord's prayer very much confused me.

11:47.007 --> 11:49.089
I didn't understand what Jesus was getting at, right?

11:49.570 --> 11:52.012
But Halloween, holy, someone say holy.

11:52.973 --> 11:53.633
Thank you, right?

11:53.673 --> 11:56.276
So holiness, what does this mean, right?

11:56.476 --> 11:58.078
What does holy actually mean?

11:58.138 --> 12:00.900
What does it mean that we love a holy God?

12:01.861 --> 12:11.250
Well, first things first, holy is not some sort of, it's not just a quirky personality trait, it's not,

12:11.586 --> 12:13.449
a characteristic, right?

12:13.950 --> 12:16.614
It is what God is made of, right?

12:16.674 --> 12:18.336
It is who God is.

12:18.416 --> 12:21.281
So holiness is the substance of God, right?

12:21.922 --> 12:33.219
And what holiness means, what they've taught us in seminary, is that holiness literally translates to set apart, set apart, which means completely other.

12:33.780 --> 12:36.604
Like God is so much not like us, that he is completely other.

12:36.644 --> 12:40.370
It's something that is hard for us to wrap our heads around.

12:41.954 --> 12:44.918
And it's not just though that God is completely different than us.

12:45.519 --> 12:50.647
He's completely different than us because he is perfectly good, perfectly good.

12:52.189 --> 12:57.757
He is perfect in his love and in his justice and in his mercy.

12:58.117 --> 13:00.701
He is pure and uncorrupted.

13:00.982 --> 13:03.205
We can't fathom that because we're not like that.

13:03.766 --> 13:09.554
But every aspect of who God is, every aspect of God's character is perfect.

13:10.850 --> 13:18.922
And what I want you to hear this morning that I think is so important too is that God is not holy because he remains removed from us.

13:19.443 --> 13:25.091
Like God has not made holy because he's separate from us and we're so disgusting that we would come in and ruin his holiness.

13:25.131 --> 13:26.753
That's not how God stays perfect.

13:26.773 --> 13:29.938
God doesn't stay perfectly good because God avoids us.

13:32.542 --> 13:38.130
God is holy because he can enter our brokenness without being corrupted by it.

13:40.450 --> 13:45.898
God is holy because he can enter our brokenness without being corrupted by it.

13:48.041 --> 13:49.984
We have a holy God who touches lepers.

13:51.406 --> 13:53.950
We have a holy God who eats with sinners.

13:54.972 --> 14:04.466
We have a holy God who invites children to come to him, who forgives enemies, who can be crucified on a tree and say, Father, forgive them, they know not what they do.

14:05.442 --> 14:16.013
We have a God who steps into our mess and into our murkiness and into our own corruptibility and remains completely and perfectly good.

14:17.655 --> 14:21.659
So holiness in Jesus is radiant goodness.

14:22.340 --> 14:28.987
It is love without selfishness, justice, without cruelty, mercy, without compromise.

14:29.308 --> 14:35.154
And I want you to also know that in scripture, a name is not just a label.

14:36.002 --> 14:40.867
So when we talk about God being holy, we're kind of naming God holy.

14:41.167 --> 14:44.450
And that isn't a label, that's not just a sign that we attach to God.

14:45.992 --> 14:54.760
In scripture, in the ancient Near East culture, a name represents your reputation and your honor.

14:57.863 --> 15:05.330
So when we say that God is holy, we are making a claim about God's honor, about God's character, about God's

15:05.410 --> 15:06.291
reputation.

15:07.694 --> 15:12.201
And there's a passage in Ezekiel that sometimes gets taken out of context.

15:12.902 --> 15:16.868
And it says that the people have profaned God's holy name.

15:19.493 --> 15:24.621
And we tend to think of that as taking the Lord's name in vain is how we interpret that.

15:25.001 --> 15:27.165
But that's not actually what Ezekiel is saying.

15:27.265 --> 15:32.914
He's not just saying that they mispronounce God's name or that they use God's name as a swear.

15:33.250 --> 15:42.101
When Ezekiel says that the Lord is upset because they profane his holy name, what he's saying is I'm upset because people are misrepresenting me.

15:45.024 --> 15:47.868
Their lives made him look unlike himself.

15:49.169 --> 15:49.710
Does that make sense?

15:49.730 --> 15:59.762
So like what they're saying is what God is upset about in this passage is that people are saying that they worship a holy God and that they know that God is holy, but then they live as if that's not true.

16:01.058 --> 16:04.582
And that upsets God because it's misrepresenting his character.

16:06.344 --> 16:12.270
So when we pray, hallelujah be thy name, we're asking for far more than just personal piety, y'all.

16:13.511 --> 16:17.235
We're asking that the world would see God as he truly is.

16:17.295 --> 16:21.380
And that includes how we reflect him.

16:21.960 --> 16:30.930
Because whether we like it or not, if we claim Christ and we claim that Christ is holy, then people look at us to see if we really believe that or not.

16:31.714 --> 16:34.497
They look at us because we claim to be little Christians, right?

16:34.517 --> 16:35.779
That's what it means, little Christ.

16:36.079 --> 16:40.545
They look at us and they see how we treat other people on Facebook and they're like, well, I don't know about that.

16:41.646 --> 16:46.051
Or they look at us driving with road rage and they think, I don't know about that.

16:46.552 --> 16:52.459
We are always being watched because we are claiming to be Christ like we are claiming to love Jesus.

16:52.860 --> 17:01.330
And so we had better start acting like it because, and this should really humble us, if God is holy and we carry his name,

17:01.826 --> 17:09.156
And we claim to believe that God is holy, then how we live either clarifies that or distorts that, right?

17:10.518 --> 17:24.977
This is a big deal to say that God is holy, to say that we believe that God is holy is a big deal because if we act as if we don't believe that that's true, it can misrepresent God's character.

17:27.661 --> 17:31.666
When we pray, how it would be in our name, it is a big,

17:31.874 --> 17:32.274
Deal.

17:35.619 --> 17:37.781
I also want to take just a second and say this.

17:38.882 --> 17:46.672
When we pray this prayer, when we pray how it would be the name, we don't make God holy just by saying those words, right?

17:47.393 --> 17:50.416
We are acknowledging that God already is holy.

17:51.397 --> 17:59.287
So when we are praying this and we are together as a community coming together saying, God, we believe that you were utterly good.

18:00.388 --> 18:01.810
You were utterly trustworthy.

18:02.338 --> 18:04.821
You are completely other in your purity.

18:04.841 --> 18:06.943
When we say God, how would be thy name?

18:06.983 --> 18:09.647
We are saying you are holy, we are not.

18:12.430 --> 18:18.277
And that distinction really matters because we know about ourselves, right?

18:18.297 --> 18:23.563
Like we know that we're impulsive and we know that we are inconsistent.

18:24.404 --> 18:29.490
We know that we oftentimes justify ourselves and we converse

18:29.570 --> 18:32.235
grudges and we love conditionally.

18:34.358 --> 18:35.620
That's just a part of being human.

18:35.641 --> 18:35.981
We do.

18:36.302 --> 18:37.664
We say our love is unconditional.

18:37.704 --> 18:38.085
It's not.

18:38.886 --> 18:40.569
It's not like we love conditionally, right?

18:40.589 --> 18:42.012
That's just honesty.

18:43.895 --> 18:45.177
God does not do that though.

18:46.379 --> 18:48.583
God is not like us.

18:48.663 --> 18:50.386
His mercy does not

18:50.498 --> 19:20.370
Fluctuate with mood his justice is never corrupted his love does not grow tired or weary He is holy and we are not That is why we need grace friends And so if we go back to Hebrews We see something deeper at play here Because the writer of Hebrews tells us not only that God is holy

19:20.706 --> 19:23.349
but that God is calling us to be holy too.

19:23.369 --> 19:29.975
This is great, terrible news, right?

19:30.195 --> 19:35.761
He says, make every effort to be holy because without holiness, no one will see the Lord.

19:37.462 --> 19:40.585
Without holiness, no one will see the Lord.

19:40.865 --> 19:42.767
Holiness is very important to God.

19:44.309 --> 19:49.714
And I find it absolutely fascinating and compelling that that verse pursue holiness.

19:51.234 --> 19:52.395
Because without it, you won't see the Lord.

19:52.616 --> 19:57.561
That verse comes at the tail end of nine verses about discipline.

19:59.163 --> 20:00.225
I don't think that's random.

20:03.408 --> 20:09.095
In this passage, I see a God who does not simply just call us holy and move on.

20:11.117 --> 20:13.060
God is in the business of forming us.

20:13.941 --> 20:18.546
God is in the business of shaping us, transforming us.

20:19.906 --> 20:22.990
Like this is training, this is work.

20:24.892 --> 20:29.318
And so I was trying to think through examples of what discipline actually looks like in practical life.

20:29.338 --> 20:31.400
Like what does it mean that God disciplines us?

20:32.161 --> 20:35.845
Because again, some of us may think of God spliting us and that's not what we're talking about, right?

20:36.286 --> 20:49.362
Like I think that discipline looks like God helping us step into the best version of ourselves, which means that sometimes it looks like conviction.

20:51.746 --> 21:00.739
That moment when the Spirit nudges you and you know you may have spoken out of pride or anger or selfishness, like discipline looks like conviction.

21:02.001 --> 21:17.042
Or sometimes it may even look like repentance, naming your sin before God honestly, instead of excusing your sin, instead of ignoring your sin, coming before him and saying, Lord, I messed up and I don't want to again.

21:18.690 --> 21:30.483
And then sometimes I think the discipline of God looks a little bit like pruning, like God gently cutting away habits and behaviors and attachments that keep you from loving well.

21:32.665 --> 21:36.609
And pruning is not comfortable but neither is surgery and both are necessary for healing, right?

21:38.291 --> 21:48.562
So the discipline of God, conviction, repentance, pruning, like that seminal classic Disney song,

21:48.994 --> 21:51.717
God is trying to make something out of us.

21:52.057 --> 21:59.724
God is trying to help us achieve that best version of ourselves that we can only achieve when we are living in relationship with Him.

21:59.744 --> 22:04.729
And the reality is pursuing holiness is hard work.

22:05.650 --> 22:08.272
It requires effort on our behalf.

22:08.672 --> 22:11.555
No one ever said that this Christian thing is supposed to be easy.

22:13.637 --> 22:18.962
Being a Christian doesn't mean that we just come and sit in this room on a Sunday morning and then call it for the rest of the week.

22:20.706 --> 22:24.530
We are a people that is constantly in training.

22:26.252 --> 22:30.516
And our training looks like that conviction of sin and behaviors that don't honor God.

22:30.556 --> 22:33.479
Looks like repenting and actually acknowledging that we sin.

22:33.819 --> 22:35.161
Methodists don't like to talk about sin.

22:35.201 --> 22:35.841
I've learned that.

22:36.222 --> 22:39.225
I've only been a Methodist since 2019, but before that I was a Baptist.

22:39.245 --> 22:40.726
And we love to talk about sin.

22:41.367 --> 22:41.507
Okay?

22:41.908 --> 22:42.788
We talked about sin.

22:42.808 --> 22:44.670
That's the only thing we talked about nine times out of 10.

22:44.730 --> 22:46.692
It was go tell other people that they're sinners though, right?

22:46.712 --> 22:48.274
Like so it was evangelism and sin.

22:48.578 --> 22:54.687
Methodists are a little uncomfortable talking about sin, and I get it, because especially in the deep sound, we get brow beaten with it a lot.

22:56.229 --> 22:58.913
But the reality is we have to acknowledge that we sin.

22:59.995 --> 23:06.144
We have to talk about the fact that we're kind of messed up, which means that we do kind of messed up things.

23:06.965 --> 23:09.949
And it doesn't necessarily mean that everyone is a murderer, right?

23:10.410 --> 23:16.018
But it does mean that, like, we gossip, and we belittle people, and we

23:16.098 --> 23:20.624
get angry when we shouldn't, we want revenge when it's not ours to take.

23:20.684 --> 23:24.129
Like we are petty people because we're human.

23:26.111 --> 23:39.670
So the way that God disciplines us sometimes is actually convicting us of sin, which means that we go to the foot of the cross and we lay down certain behaviors and we lay down certain attachments and we lay down certain addictions and then we don't pick it back up again.

23:42.293 --> 23:42.994
Repentance.

23:45.058 --> 23:50.528
And then God will come in and remove the things that we need Him to remove.

23:50.588 --> 23:57.561
We have to allow God's discipline to come in and prune our hearts, take out the things that we're carrying that are not ours to carry.

23:57.982 --> 24:04.113
Sometimes the things that God needs to come in and take out of ourselves to take out of our hearts is not even a sin.

24:04.193 --> 24:05.636
It's not something that we did.

24:05.716 --> 24:09.042
Maybe it's something that was done to you, right?

24:09.122 --> 24:14.167
Like the things that we carry with us, sometimes it's not even guilt over the things that we have done.

24:14.208 --> 24:18.212
It's things that have happened to us and the Lord needs to come in and prune that out of us.

24:18.332 --> 24:19.113
It is work.

24:20.775 --> 24:21.776
This is hard.

24:26.341 --> 24:28.944
Training only makes sense if you know what you're training for though, right?

24:29.945 --> 24:34.930
Like no one ever trained for marathon without knowing when the marathon was or which race they're racing in, right?

24:36.610 --> 24:39.673
Surgeons don't train just to hold a scalpel and stand there, right?

24:39.693 --> 24:41.034
Like there's a purpose to this.

24:41.495 --> 24:42.135
There has to be.

24:42.195 --> 24:43.917
So what are we training for?

24:43.997 --> 24:45.298
What is the goal of all this?

24:45.699 --> 24:48.702
What's the point of this conviction and repentance and pruning?

24:49.983 --> 24:52.425
Well, it isn't just rule following for the sake of rule following.

24:53.727 --> 24:55.889
And it's surely not about religious performance.

24:57.390 --> 25:01.614
This is not about managing your image so that you look like a hallmark Christian, okay?

25:03.656 --> 25:05.618
The goal for this work

25:06.306 --> 25:09.249
for all this effort is holiness.

25:12.232 --> 25:15.315
John Wesley described holiness as love excluding sin.

25:17.698 --> 25:23.964
Holiness is love excluding sin, not love excluding people, love excluding sin.

25:26.146 --> 25:33.714
And like we talked about earlier then, holiness is not about this cold distance from God or from each other,

25:34.498 --> 25:42.647
Holiness is about love being purified, love without cruelty, love without pride, love without self-protection.

25:42.707 --> 25:45.290
That's what God is trying to form in us.

25:45.610 --> 25:51.357
The basis of everything that God does for us, this is like a secret, I think, because we don't talk about it a lot and I wish that more pastors did.

25:51.717 --> 25:59.986
The whole point for all of this church stuff, the whole point for this whole Christian journey hinges on one thing and it's love.

26:01.282 --> 26:01.643
That's it.

26:01.703 --> 26:02.664
We make it so complicated.

26:03.025 --> 26:03.225
Love.

26:03.365 --> 26:06.791
Jesus loved us enough to come and die for our sins so that we could spend eternity with Him.

26:08.273 --> 26:08.694
It's love.

26:09.876 --> 26:13.662
Our mission as Christians, the number one thing that Jesus tells us to do.

26:14.202 --> 26:15.705
Love God, love your neighbors.

26:17.568 --> 26:19.250
It's all about love.

26:21.374 --> 26:24.018
And Hebrews reminds us that God is going to discipline us.

26:24.194 --> 26:35.587
because he loves us, not because he's angry, not because he's disappointed, but because he intends to share his holiness with his children, which brings us again to Lent.

26:38.010 --> 26:39.712
Lent is a training season.

26:41.133 --> 26:48.141
Lent is when the church intentionally slows down and allows God to search us.

26:49.863 --> 26:52.146
This is a season for fasting,

26:53.090 --> 26:55.213
This is a season for confession.

26:55.273 --> 26:58.899
This is the season for repentance.

27:00.622 --> 27:08.454
This is a time where we're invited to sit and analyze our lives honestly, not to earn grace, but to make space for it.

27:11.299 --> 27:13.282
And here's where it gets a little interesting, I think.

27:14.825 --> 27:18.671
We all want the good life, whatever that means to you, right?

27:18.691 --> 27:20.754
Like, but we all want some version of the good life.

27:20.834 --> 27:25.699
We may not all agree on what good means, but our culture defines good as whatever makes us happy.

27:26.700 --> 27:26.961
Okay.

27:28.683 --> 27:35.730
Scripture, Lent invites us to remember that the good life is not whatever makes us happy.

27:35.750 --> 27:37.412
It's whatever makes us holy.

27:38.974 --> 27:39.234
Okay.

27:43.058 --> 27:44.320
Happiness is fragile, y'all.

27:45.101 --> 27:47.644
It rises and falls with our circumstances.

27:48.384 --> 27:49.906
Holiness runs deeper.

27:51.298 --> 27:54.142
holiness is what studies you in Christ.

27:56.686 --> 27:59.390
And that studied life looks like love.

28:00.392 --> 28:04.698
That studied life of being rooted in Jesus when we are actively pursuing holiness.

28:04.999 --> 28:11.989
When we are allowing Jesus to come in and convict, allowing us to repent, allowing us to give up the things that we need to give up.

28:12.029 --> 28:17.838
When we do that, we start to look more like Jesus.

28:17.898 --> 28:20.402
We start to have more patience when we're irritated.

28:21.186 --> 28:23.630
We start to have more mercy when we've been wronged.

28:23.971 --> 28:29.101
We start to develop self-control in a new way when it would be easier to lash out.

28:29.381 --> 28:32.827
We start to have humility when we would rather defend ourselves.

28:33.228 --> 28:40.341
The way that we become better versions of ourselves is by pursuing holiness and allowing Jesus' love to do a good work within us.

28:42.505 --> 28:45.170
And if you hear nothing else this morning, I want you to hear this.

28:46.946 --> 29:07.168
Remember, if the enemy can quietly erode your capacity to love, if evil can come in and make you cynical and harsh and overly self-protective, then he has weakened your resemblance to Christ because love is what makes you look the most like Christ.

29:09.991 --> 29:11.893
Holiness is love shaped and steady by God.

29:15.897 --> 29:16.498
And this is

29:16.706 --> 29:18.829
hard, like I've been saying, hard work.

29:20.612 --> 29:22.295
This kind of formation takes effort.

29:23.096 --> 29:26.381
This kind of formation takes humility, takes surrender.

29:26.401 --> 29:30.287
It stretches us, but it leads somewhere good.

29:32.691 --> 29:36.978
So when we pray howl would be thy name, we're not just admiring God's holiness from a distance.

29:37.730 --> 29:42.837
we are asking that his name would be honored in the world, that his name would be honored through our own actions.

29:43.138 --> 29:48.726
When we pray, Halle would be thy name, we are saying, God, I don't wanna misrepresent your character, help me to live like you.

29:49.146 --> 30:02.986
And so my hope, and my prayer for us, as a church living in the world, in this day and age, at this particular time, in this particular space, that our prayers would start to sound more like this.

30:04.869 --> 30:05.650
Holy God.

30:07.362 --> 30:10.185
Do not let my own pride distort your mercy.

30:11.907 --> 30:14.431
Do not let my bitterness distort your love.

30:15.732 --> 30:18.696
Do not let my impatience distort your grace.

30:20.177 --> 30:22.300
Show me what it mean does not reflect you.

30:23.642 --> 30:25.344
Give me the courage to confess it.

30:26.325 --> 30:28.047
Give me the grace to release it.

30:28.087 --> 30:31.171
Train my heart to love like yours.

30:32.172 --> 30:33.674
Make your name beautiful in me.

30:33.714 --> 30:37.298
And all God's people would say, amen.

